name: Kennedy Rocker by P&P Chair Company
description:
$275 each or $500 for the pair! That's 50% off the retail price! These chairs are brand new - still have the tags on them!

The signature 1920's design is roomy and comfortable. But don't let the traditional styling fool you. When it comes to relieving today's stress, it is state-of-the-art. The back posts and back rails are steam bent providing the right amount of support at spinal pressure points due to curving around the shoulders and at the lower back. The cane seat and back offer firm yet natural spring. Set low for comfortable elbow support, it has wide armrests for perfect balance. Also, the arm rests are lower than similar rockers, allowing the sitter’s arm to relax naturally at the sides of the body. Elegant turned posts and cane accents make a presidential statement in any setting.

Design: North American Oak frame with hand woven rattan seat and back.
Finishes: Hand rubbed stains with a lacquer top coat (for indoor use only): Natural Oak.
Dimensions: Back Height to top of curved back rail: 43”, Seat Height: 16 ½”, Seat: 22 ½” x 17”, Seat to top of arm: 8”, Arms: 4” at widest point. 
Weight: 30 lbs. , 35 lbs. with carton. Two rocking chairs in a carton 65 lbs. Carton size for one rocker 48”x35”x28” for two rockers 47”x29”x35”

Cushion Set included with each chair (a $90 option at P&P Chair Co.)

name: Set of 4 Shabby Chic Cherub Plates
description:
These 4 plates evoke a very shabby chic or Paris flea market feeling.  In various pastel colors with hand painted cherub centers, vestiges of gold leaf at the edges, they make a great grouping to hang on the wall. Circa 1890-1920, these were typically painted by well-to-do ladies on white ware that was imported from Europe specifically for the china painting craze that was sweeping the states. 

The plates measure approx. 9" each and are in very vintage condition. The yellow plate has a crack visible on the back but it does not show through to the front. The blue, lavender and yellow plates each have a small amount of adulteration to the glaze but mostly on the back sides. The peach plate is in remarkably good condition for a 100 year old piece.
